3 MEDICAID Acceptance

We seem to have many physicians who dont accept MEDICAID. Should them enter the analysis? It seems that these physicians would not be part of the eligible sample if the goal is to see if individuals who accept both leaves you weiting longer if you are on Medicaid. The research question would be: Do providers make patients to wait longer if they are on Medicaid, as compared to Blue Cross? I understand that here the provider must accept both.

If we include all physicians, then the research question is more like: If I have Medicaid, do I wait longer when I try to book an appointment?

Here we add a variable to the dataset that flag providers who have at least one occurrence of “Physician does not accept MEDICAID”.

med <- final2 %>% 
  dplyr::filter(Reason.for.exclusions == "Physician does not accept MEDICAID") %>% 
  dplyr::select(NPI) %>% 
  group_by(NPI) %>% 
  summarise(N = n()) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-N) %>% 
  mutate(No_Medicaid = 1)

final3 <- left_join(final2,med) %>% 
  mutate(No_Medicaid = factor(ifelse(is.na(No_Medicaid),0,1),
                              labels= c("Yes Medicaid","No Medicaid"))) %>% 
  mutate(grad = cut(Graduation.year, 
                    breaks = c(1960,1986,1993,2000,2005,2012), 
                    dig.lab = 0,include.lowest = TRUE)) %>% 
  rename(ntransf = Number.of.Transfers..phone.call.transferred.from.one.person.or.answering.service.to.the.next.,
         reason = Reason.for.exclusions,
         days = Business.days.until.appointment,
         title = Professional.Title.Merged
         )


ggplot(dplyr::filter(final3,insurance_type == "Medicaid"),
       aes(x = No_Medicaid))+
  geom_bar(fill = "gray80")+
  geom_text(stat='count', aes(label=..count..), vjust= 1)+
  ggtitle("Distribution of MADICAID Acceptance")+
  facet_wrap(~insurance_type)+
  theme_minimal()

7 Descriptives

7.1 All 800 Providers

There are 800 providers in the dataset. These are all sampled providers. Many of these providers could not be contacted. In the paper we probably want to report characteristics of contacted providers who have at least one waiting time and are therefore included in the analysis.

Total column is at the provider level. Not meaningful with insurance specific variables, like day of the week.

Insurance Type columns are at the Insurance Type level. Not meaningful with provider level variables.

MEDICAID Acceptance columns are at the provider level. Not meaningful with insurance specific variables.

In the Analysis columns are at the provider level. Not meaningful with insurance specific variables. Here, In the Analysis means those providers that have data for number of days until appointment, and therefore will be used in the analysis. A comparison between “In the Analsyis” and “Not in the Analysis” may give an idea of bias in the data, that is, what kind of proviers were easier to reach and because of that are more represented in the sample than they should.

final4.half <- filter(final4, insurance_type == "Medicaid")

              group_by(NPI) %>%

7.2.1 Statistical Tests

Here we conduct statistical tests to see if the profile differs for those who accept Medicaid and those who dont. This analysis is only valid for variables that dont change with insurance type. It is not valid for variables that change, like Day of the Week.

# temp is the dataset with only contacted providers. 
blong <- filter(temp, insurance_type == "Medicaid")

vars <- c("gender","Age","age_category","subspecialty","provider","title","grad","central",
          "ntransf","dow","reason","District")

testdata <- data.frame(variable = character(), test = character(), p.value = double())
for (i in vars){
  p <- sum((names(blong) == i)*(seq(1,ncol(blong))))
  #print(paste0("Variable = ",i,", Position =",p ))
  if (is.numeric(blong[[p]])){
    w <- wilcox.test(blong[[p]] ~ blong$No_Medicaid)
    temp2 <- data.frame(variable = i,test = "Wilcox",p.value = w$p.value)
  } else{
    w <- fisher.test(blong[[p]] , blong$No_Medicaid, simulate.p.value = T, B=100000)
    temp2 <- data.frame(variable = i,test = "Fisher",p.value = w$p.value)
  }
  
testdata <- rbind(testdata,temp2)
  
}

kable(testdata, caption = "p-values for association between Accepting Medicaid and other variables in the dataset") %>% 
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

7.2.2 Association Physician Age and Medicaid Acceptance

This is related to reviewer request in the second revision.

# Age in Years - Mann-Whitney non-parametric test
wilcox.test(temp.half$Age ~ temp.half$No_Medicaid)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  temp.half$Age by temp.half$No_Medicaid
## W = 2540, p-value = 0.1079
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
# Age Groups - Fisher Test.
fisher.test(temp.half$age_category, temp.half$No_Medicaid)
## 
##  Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data

7.3.1 Statistical Test

blong <- final4.half
vars <- c("gender","Age","age_category","subspecialty","provider","title","grad",
          "central","ntransf","District")

testdata2 <- data.frame(variable = character(), test = character(), p.value = double())
for (i in vars){
  p <- sum((names(blong) == i)*(seq(1,ncol(blong))))
  #print(paste0("Variable = ",i,", Position =",p ))
  if (is.numeric(blong[[p]])){
    w <- wilcox.test(blong[[p]] ~ blong$No_Medicaid)
    temp2 <- data.frame(variable = i,test = "Wilcox",p.value = w$p.value)
  } else{
    w <- fisher.test(blong[[p]] , blong$No_Medicaid, simulate.p.value = T, B=100000)
    temp2 <- data.frame(variable = i,test = "Fisher",p.value = w$p.value)
  }
  
testdata2 <- rbind(testdata2,temp2)
  
}

8.3 New Control Variables

Compared to the previous version of this report, we are adding new control variables to the models. They are District, Age Category, Reason for Exclusions and Number of Transfers.

Reason and Number of Transfer were added because they are different across insurance types.

From the new variables in the dataset, Urban/ Rural was not used because thre are very few non-Urban Providers. State was also not used because of the very large number of categories. Instead we use District, which are groupings of the States.

Note - We have tried using States as random effected, with NPI nested into it, but the final model has all sort of convergence problems and the insurance type effect is the same. So we prefer to go with the simpler, more parcimonious model which just controls for Districts instead.

8.4.2 Over-dispersion

Here we use a function to check for over-dispersion. It looks like we are fine, although there may be some under-dispersion.

In order to have an idea if there is over-dispersion we divide the Pearson Chi-square by the degree of freedom of the residuals. This ratio should be around 1, with values larger then 1 indicating over-dispersion and lower than 1 indicating under-dispersion. In our case we get the value 0.74 which indicates some under-dispersion. However, if we have underdispersion, our p-value is going to be conservative (lerger than it should be), so that a significant p-value will be even more significant under under-dispersion.

overdisp_fun <- function(model) {
    rdf <- df.residual(model)
    rp <- residuals(model,type="pearson")
    Pearson.chisq <- sum(rp^2)
    prat <- Pearson.chisq/rdf
    pval <- pchisq(Pearson.chisq, df=rdf, lower.tail=FALSE)
    c(chisq=Pearson.chisq,ratio=prat,rdf=rdf,p=pval)
}
overdisp_fun(lmmodel1)
##       chisq       ratio         rdf           p 
## 483.5260619   0.7578778 638.0000000   0.9999988

9.2 Comparison Insurance Type

A few variables vary within Provider, across Insurance Types. It might be important to be aware of differences in these variables.

9.2.1 Day of the Week

The usual McNemar test is conducted when there are only two categories, and a generalizaiton of it, the McNemar–Bowker chi-square tests is used for more than two categories.

Day of the Week is highly signfiicant, which means that there is evidence of change in the distribution of Day of the Week when we move from one insurance type to the other.

library(rcompanion)

x <- final5$dow[final5$insurance_type == "Medicaid"]
y <- final5$dow[final5$insurance_type == "Blue Cross/Shield"]

mcnemar.test(x,y)
## 
##  McNemar's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  x and y
## McNemar's chi-squared = 153.97, df = 10, p-value < 2.2e-16

9.3.1 Statistical Tests

Here we compare providers who accept both with those who dont, using only the 477 providers with some data (that is, we want to see if tthe providers used in this analysis are different from the providers in the previous analysis).

We find some evidence of differences.

# temp is the dataset with only contacted providers. 
blong <- filter(temp, insurance_type == "Medicaid")

vars <- c("gender","Age","age_category","subspecialty","provider","title","grad","central",
          "ntransf","dow","reason","District")

testdata <- data.frame(variable = character(), test = character(), p.value = double())
for (i in vars){
  p <- sum((names(blong) == i)*(seq(1,ncol(blong))))
  #print(paste0("Variable = ",i,", Position =",p ))
  if (is.numeric(blong[[p]])){
    w <- wilcox.test(blong[[p]] ~ blong$No_Medicaid)
    temp2 <- data.frame(variable = i,test = "Wilcox",p.value = w$p.value)
  } else{
    w <- fisher.test(blong[[p]] , blong$No_Medicaid, simulate.p.value = T, B=100000)
    temp2 <- data.frame(variable = i,test = "Fisher",p.value = w$p.value)
  }
  
testdata <- rbind(testdata,temp2)
  
}

kable(testdata, caption = "p-values for association between Accepting Medicaid and other variables in the dataset") %>% 
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

9.4.1 Over-dispersion

Here we use a function to check for over-dispersion. It looks like we are fine, although there may be some under-dispersion.

In order to have an idea if there is over-dispersion we divide the Pearson Chi-square by the degree of freedom of the residuals. This ratio should be around 1, with values larger then 1 indicating over-dispersion and lower than 1 indicating under-dispersion. In our case we get the value 0.84 which indicates some under-dispersion. However, if we have underdispersion, our p-value is going to be conservative (lerger than it should be), so that a significant p-value will be even more significant under under-dispersion.

overdisp_fun <- function(model) {
    rdf <- df.residual(model)
    rp <- residuals(model,type="pearson")
    Pearson.chisq <- sum(rp^2)
    prat <- Pearson.chisq/rdf
    pval <- pchisq(Pearson.chisq, df=rdf, lower.tail=FALSE)
    c(chisq=Pearson.chisq,ratio=prat,rdf=rdf,p=pval)
}
overdisp_fun(lmmodel1)
##       chisq       ratio         rdf           p 
## 422.7413152   0.8421142 502.0000000   0.9956718

9.4.2.3 Generalizing Estimating Equation

GEE models dont have the same problem of over-dispersion as mixed poisson models, as it allows for a scale parameter and robust variance estimators. Here we see an increase of 52% in waiting time, which is again close to the poisson model indicating that the results from the mixed poisson model should be reasonable.

          subspecialty +
